{{Short description|Sacred locations in Shinto}}
[[File:Miwayama201805.jpg|thumb|300x300px|[[Ōmiwa Shrine|Omiwa Shrine]] has [[Mount Miwa]] as its [[Shintai]] and does not have a [[Shinto architecture|honden]].{{Citation needed|date=March 2023}}<ref name="Tamura20">Tamura, page 21</ref>]] {{Nihongo|Kannabi|神奈備|Kamunabi / Kannabi / Kaminabi}} refers to a region in [[shinto]] that is a [[Shintai]] itself, or hosts a kami.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web |title=Encyclopedia of Shinto詳細 |url=https://d-museum.kokugakuin.ac.jp//eos/detail/ |access-date=2023-03-10 |website=國學院大學デジタルミュージアム |language=ja}}</ref> They are generally either [[Mountain worship|mountains]] or [[Chinju no Mori|forests]].<ref name=":0" /><ref name=":1">[[富士山|霊峰富士]]など。[[山岳信仰]]を参照</ref>
They may be host to [[Shinboku]] (sacred trees), or [[Iwakura rocks]]<ref name=":1" />
Although natural locations, Kannabi will still have [[Shimenawa]], [[Torii]], and [[Sandō]] marking the path towards them.{{Citation needed|date=March 2023}}
[[Nachi Falls]] is considered a Kannabi<ref name="nachi2">{{cite web |last=Kamizaka |first=Jirō |title=Hiryū Gongen |url=http://www.kkr.mlit.go.jp/wakayama/rekishi/disco131.html |access-date=28 March 2010 |publisher=Ministry of Land, Infrastructure and Transport - Kinki Regional Development Bureau |language=ja}}</ref>, as is [[Mount Miwa]].<ref name="Tamura20" />
Shrines dedicated to Kannabi often lack [[Haiden (Shinto)|worship halls]] or [[honden|hondens]] and instead enshrine the natural kannabis as deities. [[Ōmiwa Shrine]] is one such example.{{Citation needed|date=March 2023}}
