[[File:Miwayama201805.jpg|thumb|300x300px|[[Ōmiwa Shrine|Omiwa Shrine]] has [[Mount Miwa]] as its [[Shintai]] and does not have a [[Shinto architecture|honden]].<ref name=":2">{{cite book |last=Tamura |first=Yoshiro |title=Japanese Buddhism - A Cultural History |publisher=Kosei Publishing Company |year=2000 |isbn=4-333-01684-3 |location=Tokyo |pages=21 |chapter=The Birth of the Japanese Nation}}</ref>]] {{Nihongo|'''''Kannabi'''''|神奈備}}, also '''''kaminabi''''' or '''''kamunabi''''', refers to a region in [[Shinto]] that is a ''[[shintai]]'' (repositories in which ''[[kami]]'' reside) itself, or hosts a ''kami''.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web |title=Encyclopedia of Shinto詳細 |url=https://d-museum.kokugakuin.ac.jp//eos/detail/ |access-date=2023-03-10 |website=國學院大學デジタルミュージアム |language=ja}}</ref> They are generally either [[Mountain worship|mountains]] or [[Chinju no Mori|forests]].<ref name=":0" /><ref name=":1">[[富士山|霊峰富士]]など。[[山岳信仰]]を参照</ref> [[Nachi Falls]] is considered a ''kannabi'',<ref name="nachi2">{{cite web |last=Kamizaka |first=Jirō |title=Hiryū Gongen |url=http://www.kkr.mlit.go.jp/wakayama/rekishi/disco131.html |access-date=28 March 2010 |publisher=Ministry of Land, Infrastructure and Transport - Kinki Regional Development Bureau |language=ja}}</ref> as is [[Mount Miwa]].<ref name=":2" />
== Overview == They may be host to ''[[shinboku]]'' (sacred trees), or [[Iwakura rocks]]<ref name=":1" /> They may have ''[[shimenawa]]'', ''[[torii]]'', and ''[[sandō]]'' marking the path towards them.{{Citation needed|date=March 2023}}
Shrines dedicated to ''kannabi'' often lack a ''[[honden]]'' or [[Haiden (Shinto)|''haiden'']], and instead enshrine the natural ''kannabi'' as deities. [[Ōmiwa Shrine]] is one such example.<ref name=":2" /> {{Interlanguage link|Kanasana Jinja|ja|金鑚神社}} also has its mountain be its Shintai<ref name=":12">{{Cite web |title=Glossary of Shinto Names and Terms: K |url=https://www2.kokugakuin.ac.jp/ijcc/wp/glossary/def_K.html |access-date=2023-04-06 |website=www2.kokugakuin.ac.jp}}</ref>
